107
00:09:24,360 --> 00:09:26,280
Hi everyone.

108
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:31,240
In this video I want to introduce you to one of Nikola Tesla's works.

109
00:09:31,980 --> 00:09:34,680
Namely his bifilar coil.

110
00:09:34,680 --> 00:09:36,800
"Bifilar" means two.

111
00:09:37,320 --> 00:09:41,320
That is, this coil is made with two wires at once.

112
00:09:42,140 --> 00:09:51,740
The wires are laid parallel to each other, and the end of one wire is directly galvanically connected to the start of the other.

113
00:09:52,380 --> 00:09:54,960
Such a coil has interesting properties.

114
00:09:55,540 --> 00:10:01,540
There's distributed capacitance throughout its conductors.

115
00:10:01,540 --> 00:10:14,140
And if you connect a coil that's several tens of meters long to a device that measures capacitance, it may show you the coil's capacitance.

116
00:10:14,860 --> 00:10:19,240
Even though it's actually a single conductor.

117
00:10:20,820 --> 00:10:25,460
We'll test this coil with this schematic.

118
00:10:26,420 --> 00:10:33,160
More precisely, we'll test several such coils connected into a single block at once.

119
00:10:33,720 --> 00:10:46,280
In this schematic, one bifilar is shown connected to the switch, and the measurement is done

120
00:10:46,280 --> 00:10:56,580
by calculating the consumed power and calculating the power going to the load.

121
00:10:57,540 --> 00:11:06,620
During the experiment we'll test 8 bifilars on one load at the same time.

122
00:11:08,680 --> 00:11:11,600
Let's look at the test device in more detail.

123
00:11:11,600 --> 00:11:21,860
We have power source 1 — this is the main power source, with a voltmeter and ammeter.

124
00:11:22,660 --> 00:11:29,300
It connects to the device input, the main cap is 47 µF at 400 V.

125
00:11:30,480 --> 00:11:38,380
And further on, from the cap, the supply voltage runs to the bifilar winding and the switch.

126
00:11:38,380 --> 00:11:55,400
The switch is controlled by a PWM regulator — a pulse-width modulation control block that can change frequency and adjust duty cycle of the signal going to

127
00:11:55,400 --> 00:11:57,780
the gate of the control transistor.

128
00:11:57,780 --> 00:12:09,080
This system uses a high-voltage power supply up to 300 V, so the switch is picked with margin at 200 V — an IRF740.

129
00:12:10,100 --> 00:12:22,820
Power source 2 can be any low-power device — in this case it'll also be a lab power supply with a voltmeter and ammeter.

130
00:12:22,820 --> 00:12:29,820
We watch the additional power that's brought to the PWM regulator.

131
00:12:30,980 --> 00:12:41,820
The PWM regulator's consumption is in the range of 1.5 watts when working with 8 switches driven by two drivers.

132
00:12:44,340 --> 00:12:59,000
Note that charged-particle movement through the switch goes from minus, through the switch and coil, and out to plus.

133
00:12:59,460 --> 00:13:06,960
While the electromotive force is directed from plus through the coil, the switch, and to minus.

134
00:13:06,960 --> 00:13:17,240
That is, the electron moves through the switch opposite to the applied potential.

135
00:13:18,640 --> 00:13:20,640
Now pay attention to the pickup.

136
00:13:21,060 --> 00:13:23,320
The pickup is done very interestingly.

137
00:13:24,580 --> 00:13:36,720
The pickup goes through a diode connected directly to the end of the bifilar winding where it joins the switch's drain.

138
00:13:36,960 --> 00:13:44,740
And the second side of the pickup is connected to the start of the coil.

139
00:13:45,400 --> 00:13:55,000
You can see that the power source voltage can't go directly to the load.

140
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:07,920
Since during electron movement it's blocked by the diode, and on this side it also won't go since the chain is closed.

141
00:14:08,260 --> 00:14:10,700
There it is — the first circuit, the closed system.

142
00:14:11,220 --> 00:14:17,220
The second circuit is an open system relative to the first.

143
00:14:17,300 --> 00:14:24,920
And the open system consists of the bifilar winding, diode, reservoir cap, voltmeter,

144
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:26,480
ammeter, and load.

145
00:14:27,560 --> 00:14:40,020
If we examine this schematic in detail, you can see that galvanic isolation is implemented between the power source and the load.

146
00:14:40,020 --> 00:14:52,480
This way we can detect the so-called response from the environment that we'll see on the bifilar winding.

147
00:14:53,280 --> 00:14:59,320
And this response from the environment is exactly what we'll observe acting on the load.

148
00:15:00,280 --> 00:15:03,380
Here it's appropriate to immediately explain the term "environment".

149
00:15:03,840 --> 00:15:09,680
Nikola Tesla himself used the term "environment" in his work to refer to the ether.

150
00:15:10,020 --> 00:15:15,200
You can find a lot of info on this online.

151
00:15:16,200 --> 00:15:21,160
And I see no point in arguing whether it exists or not.

152
00:15:21,700 --> 00:15:34,280
I'll just note my observation in this area of alternative science — that this environment isn't a discrete system.

153
00:15:34,280 --> 00:15:41,860
"Discrete" means consisting of tiny particles, so-called etherons and the like.

154
00:15:42,040 --> 00:15:45,420
The environment is a purely field structure.

155
00:15:47,420 --> 00:15:54,700
The field structure can transmit oscillations — it oscillates as a whole.

156
00:15:55,700 --> 00:16:00,280
And this field structure is also not electromagnetic.

157
00:16:02,180 --> 00:16:07,120
Electromagnetic phenomena are secondary phenomena in this environment.

158
00:16:08,460 --> 00:16:15,160
There are well-known experiments in classical physics for detecting the so-called ether wind.

159
00:16:16,080 --> 00:16:21,960
And attempts to confirm the existence of the ether and the environment in general.

160
00:16:22,400 --> 00:16:24,300
They didn't meet with success.

161
00:16:25,300 --> 00:16:26,980
There's one reason.

162
00:16:28,860 --> 00:16:33,580
The misunderstanding that this environment isn't electromagnetic.

163
00:16:34,440 --> 00:16:41,080
People who tried to detect it knowingly made a gross initial error.

164
00:16:41,520 --> 00:16:54,280
You can't, with devices that register electromagnetic phenomena, catch the presence of an object that doesn't create electromagnetic disturbances.

165
00:16:54,300 --> 00:17:10,740
This environment can interact, manifest itself with our material world specifically in such a way that an intermediary is needed.

166
00:17:10,940 --> 00:17:18,680
The intermediary between this environment — the field structure — and us is the material particles.

167
00:17:19,380 --> 00:17:22,620
That is, the transfer happens through them.

168
00:17:22,700 --> 00:17:31,780
In this case, it's the free charges in the conductor, the metal crystal lattice.

169
00:17:32,180 --> 00:17:39,000
That is, we essentially judge the existence of this environment through intermediaries.

170
00:17:39,540 --> 00:17:48,020
The intermediary is an excited atom of material substance that then emits an electromagnetic wave.

171
00:17:48,680 --> 00:17:51,900
At the frequency of its oscillations — and we register it.

172
00:17:52,640 --> 00:17:54,140
Only by such a method.

173
00:17:54,320 --> 00:17:59,780
And this principle works in all the devices we try to assemble.

174
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:08,180
The main principle is that we extract energy through an intermediary.

175
00:18:08,620 --> 00:18:09,460
And no other way.

176
00:18:10,080 --> 00:18:12,580
This is important to understand.

177
00:18:12,580 --> 00:18:19,920
So — here are the oscillograms we'll observe during the schematic test.

178
00:18:21,480 --> 00:18:26,680
I highlighted the point where probe 1 is.

179
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:32,280
This will pick up the signal that controls the gate directly.

180
00:18:33,040 --> 00:18:34,980
We'll track it by voltage.

181
00:18:35,560 --> 00:18:39,280
And you need to understand that point 2 is marked here.

182
00:18:39,860 --> 00:18:42,400
At all these points there are various oscillograms.

183
00:18:42,580 --> 00:18:49,380
You need to understand that the FET transistor inverts the signal by voltage.

184
00:18:50,350 --> 00:18:54,960
In this case I specially shaded the control signal.

185
00:18:55,700 --> 00:19:03,720
And at this point on the drain — number 2 — the signal is also shaded.

186
00:19:04,360 --> 00:19:08,480
This is the voltage drop when the transistor opens.

187
00:19:08,480 --> 00:19:13,760
The supply voltage drops to zero when the switch opens.

188
00:19:14,360 --> 00:19:20,600
And if we tracked current, the current would grow as a curve.

189
00:19:21,260 --> 00:19:25,600
The current doesn't grow as sharply as the voltage can.

190
00:19:26,500 --> 00:19:34,200
Because a charged particle — in this case the electron — is a pretty heavy particle.

191
00:19:34,280 --> 00:19:37,480
And it can't break off as fast as voltage.

192
00:19:38,480 --> 00:19:40,840
So there's a time lag.

193
00:19:42,780 --> 00:19:51,040
This way we see that the voltage drop matches the control signal for the duration of the control signal.

194
00:19:51,800 --> 00:20:00,060
Next, the oscillogram is shown at nominal load when the device reaches lamp power.

195
00:20:01,380 --> 00:20:06,440
An active load was specifically chosen so it wouldn't introduce inductive disturbances.

196
00:20:06,440 --> 00:20:08,520
Like an electric motor.

197
00:20:09,800 --> 00:20:18,600
You can see the power moment matches the switch's closing time clearly.

198
00:20:18,740 --> 00:20:23,320
At this edge — when the switch closes — voltage grows.

199
00:20:23,880 --> 00:20:27,420
And here we'll see the voltage rise.

200
00:20:27,820 --> 00:20:32,460
If we consider it without load, we'll see a tall spike.

201
00:20:33,440 --> 00:20:35,880
And I want to say right away —

202
00:20:36,460 --> 00:20:39,860
this spike isn't a manifestation of back EMF.

203
00:20:40,180 --> 00:20:43,800
Back EMF is the reverse electromotive force.

204
00:20:44,380 --> 00:20:49,460
It's always directed opposite to the supply potential.

205
00:20:49,940 --> 00:20:56,960
If this phenomenon were back EMF, the oscillogram would look completely different.

206
00:20:57,620 --> 00:21:05,120
When the switch closes, the spike for us goes in the reverse direction — here.

207
00:21:05,940 --> 00:21:19,380
And during experiments I'll show this phenomenon — that no matter where we put the oscilloscope's common probe, this spike will always be positive.

208
00:21:19,380 --> 00:21:35,640
Since this spike is positive, it's evidence that these devices attract a second material particle in nature to transfer electric energy.

209
00:21:35,920 --> 00:21:39,600
Absolute dualism of everything exists in nature.

210
00:21:40,220 --> 00:21:46,600
That is, we should understand — if we have the electron, we also have the positron.

211
00:21:46,600 --> 00:22:02,600
But let me say right away — this positron isn't the particle classical science studies and tries to assemble as another killer thing, as always, an antimatter bomb.

212
00:22:03,540 --> 00:22:14,420
They actually obtain this matter — several milligrams a year — and are happy with it, already trying to attach it to dynamite.

213
00:22:14,420 --> 00:22:22,100
We need a different particle that's responsible for the electric field by its work.

214
00:22:23,580 --> 00:22:26,460
It has positive polarity.

215
00:22:27,160 --> 00:22:33,760
Now let's move to the tests and capture these oscillograms in practice.

216
00:22:34,320 --> 00:22:39,180
At the end of the experiment we'll calculate efficiency with the known formula.

217
00:22:39,180 --> 00:22:52,800
Efficiency in percent is calculated as the ratio of the power at the load to the power brought to the device.

218
00:22:52,800 --> 00:23:10,620
I marked P2 at the lamp where voltmeter 2 and ammeter 2 are — calculate power, divide by the voltmeter-times-ammeter reading of the input power, multiply by 100.

219
00:23:10,720 --> 00:23:14,300
And calculate efficiency in percent.

220
00:23:15,140 --> 00:23:26,600
I also want to note that when studying these windings, Nikola Tesla made them with two wires and made a flat coil.

221
00:23:28,840 --> 00:23:33,300
Started twisting two wires — it spread out like a snail in a spiral.

222
00:23:33,900 --> 00:23:38,500
I made this winding not in flat form, to save space.

223
00:23:39,500 --> 00:23:48,360
These windings sit on the plastic core of the coil.

224
00:23:49,380 --> 00:23:55,660
A distinctive property of these coils is the absence of a core.

225
00:23:56,180 --> 00:23:57,700
There shouldn't be a core.

226
00:23:58,500 --> 00:24:07,040
This circuit isn't a converter — it's not a flyback variation.

227
00:24:07,040 --> 00:24:09,600
Though they're slightly similar.

228
00:24:10,380 --> 00:24:18,340
Flyback converters imply having a core and a pickup from the coil.

229
00:24:18,640 --> 00:24:26,840
In this case, in a flyback converter, this coil isn't wound as a bifilar — it's a choke.

230
00:24:27,280 --> 00:24:36,340
The switch works on the choke, the choke stores inductance as energy during operation.

231
00:24:37,040 --> 00:24:40,640
When the switch turns off, we also take through a diode to the load.

232
00:24:41,060 --> 00:24:47,780
Here the coils are made "on air" — that is, the core is absent, smallest inductance.

233
00:24:48,560 --> 00:24:54,380
And it's impossible to store an energy reserve in this inductance.

234
00:24:55,100 --> 00:25:02,040
I want to note that the distance between wires is very critical — it should be as small as possible.

235
00:25:02,040 --> 00:25:14,120
When making these coils, if they're two separate wires, I twist them into a braid with a drill or a screwdriver.

236
00:25:14,880 --> 00:25:21,960
To make them maximally close in contact through the insulation.

237
00:25:22,700 --> 00:25:25,960
The coil lengths can be different.

238
00:25:27,160 --> 00:25:33,320
And picking the frequency and pulse width is very critical.

239
00:25:34,260 --> 00:25:37,200
For each coil it's individual.

240
00:25:37,740 --> 00:25:44,640
But since I made my coils identically, one PWM regulator controls all of them.

241
00:25:48,200 --> 00:25:50,460
There's another interesting point.

242
00:25:51,360 --> 00:25:54,820
These coils don't like too big a duty cycle.

243
00:25:55,740 --> 00:26:11,340
You need to understand that if we detect the presence of a second particle responsible for energy transfer, this particle doesn't like too strong a magnetic field.

244
00:26:11,440 --> 00:26:12,800
It just doesn't work in it.

245
00:26:12,800 --> 00:26:19,700
And if the duty cycle is too big, the magnetic field will kill the whole process.

246
00:26:20,280 --> 00:26:26,800
So the control pulse duty cycle should be up to 35–40%.

247
00:26:27,420 --> 00:26:31,060
The effect shows up at duty cycle around 5%.

248
00:26:33,430 --> 00:26:37,970
Here's our test sample.

249
00:26:40,710 --> 00:26:43,890
Turned out to be a fairly big thing.

250
00:26:47,250 --> 00:26:49,190
Now I'll explain it.

251
00:26:49,810 --> 00:26:52,370
This is the heat sink.

252
00:26:52,630 --> 00:26:55,770
The switches are underneath.

253
00:26:56,830 --> 00:26:58,930
These are the bifilar leads.

254
00:26:58,930 --> 00:27:01,070
There are 8 of them.

255
00:27:01,710 --> 00:27:04,650
4 bifilars in each of the coils.

256
00:27:04,830 --> 00:27:05,730
4 bobbins here.

257
00:27:07,050 --> 00:27:15,470
These are leads going to the plus of the power source.

258
00:27:16,210 --> 00:27:18,350
These leads.

259
00:27:18,510 --> 00:27:19,930
Four wires.

260
00:27:20,890 --> 00:27:24,930
They come to the plus terminal.

261
00:27:25,730 --> 00:27:26,970
Here comes minus.

262
00:27:26,970 --> 00:27:32,470
Minus goes — same as in the schematic — to the FET sources.

263
00:27:33,230 --> 00:27:35,030
It went to the common block here.

264
00:27:35,990 --> 00:27:39,530
This is the input cap, 47 µF, 400 V.

265
00:27:39,750 --> 00:27:41,390
This is the output cap.

266
00:27:42,010 --> 00:27:49,470
The output cap is made of a pair of two 400 V electrolytics in series.

267
00:27:49,970 --> 00:27:51,270
That gives 110 µF.

268
00:27:52,330 --> 00:27:56,190
At 800 V because these spikes are very high-voltage.

269
00:27:56,970 --> 00:28:02,390
And capacitors die very fast — they pop apart.

270
00:28:02,990 --> 00:28:06,530
Because the voltage here is very high if no load is connected.

271
00:28:06,630 --> 00:28:08,910
That point needs to be noted.

272
00:28:09,330 --> 00:28:18,690
I want to point out that the environment always responds with a positive polarity pulse — and a very high-voltage one.

273
00:28:21,110 --> 00:28:27,270
This whole thing is controlled by the PWM regulator.

274
00:28:28,190 --> 00:28:28,670
Here it is.

275
00:28:30,530 --> 00:28:36,250
The chip, two drivers, and its separate power.

276
00:28:37,750 --> 00:28:40,010
Now let's connect.

277
00:28:40,010 --> 00:28:55,050
Oh yes — I specifically made a break in the tape so you could see that the wires are twisted into a braid and wound on the bobbins.

278
00:28:55,130 --> 00:28:59,370
In each bobbin there are two bifilars.

279
00:28:59,870 --> 00:29:02,050
Twisted in four wires.

280
00:29:05,990 --> 00:29:08,050
Side overview.

281
00:29:10,070 --> 00:29:11,830
We see the switches.

282
00:29:13,250 --> 00:29:14,110
Diodes visible.

283
00:29:15,230 --> 00:29:20,250
Common terminal where everything drains to the cap.

284
00:29:21,250 --> 00:29:22,730
So.

285
00:29:30,370 --> 00:29:40,030
If anyone has replicated John Bedini's device, you can see the analogy.

286
00:29:41,370 --> 00:29:47,950
In his system he used a bipolar transistor instead of a FET.

287
00:29:48,930 --> 00:29:50,370
Also used a diode.

288
00:29:50,370 --> 00:29:52,070
And a pickup.

289
00:29:54,110 --> 00:29:56,310
He usually used a battery.

290
00:29:58,410 --> 00:30:01,660
The schematic is actually very similar.

291
00:30:02,210 --> 00:30:08,750
And I'll go further — Bedini worked exactly on this principle, not on back EMF.

292
00:30:09,210 --> 00:30:17,890
Because builders of his devices got the back-EMF spike and tried to do something with it.

293
00:30:17,890 --> 00:30:24,390
Naturally that doesn't work because you can't get anywhere with back EMF.

294
00:30:25,410 --> 00:30:31,710
And this device, like his, charges batteries very well with so-called radiant energy.

295
00:30:32,070 --> 00:30:35,490
The same interesting phenomena happen here.

296
00:30:36,470 --> 00:30:50,970
Because Bedini couldn't say everything in plain text, he made a simple system in the form of a rotating wheel with magnets.

297
00:30:51,890 --> 00:30:53,510
I'd put it this way.

298
00:30:54,230 --> 00:30:57,050
For someone working in this area — they get the essence.

299
00:30:57,550 --> 00:31:03,110
For someone seeing this for the first time — it's like a magician's performance.

300
00:31:03,710 --> 00:31:11,210
If you can't say something directly, you need an information veil.

301
00:31:11,210 --> 00:31:13,410
Like magicians do.

302
00:31:13,510 --> 00:31:19,170
The beautiful assistant everyone looks at while the magician himself does his work.

303
00:31:20,050 --> 00:31:21,590
But Bedini wasn't a magician.

304
00:31:22,310 --> 00:31:28,710
His beautiful assistant was that rotating wheel that everyone paid attention to.

305
00:31:29,450 --> 00:31:37,950
This scheme is easy to implement without any rotating wheel, and it works much more effectively.

306
00:31:37,950 --> 00:31:44,410
Anyone who builds it — pay attention, it's not back EMF in his devices.

307
00:31:46,010 --> 00:31:47,590
Moving to the test.

308
00:31:48,450 --> 00:31:52,730
We'll test on a 100 W load.

309
00:31:53,810 --> 00:32:02,550
Using my test bench.

310
00:32:03,170 --> 00:32:06,130
Lamps with marked ratings here.

311
00:32:06,130 --> 00:32:09,870
Here are the voltmeter and ammeter.

312
00:32:11,570 --> 00:32:13,510
They're in groups.

313
00:32:14,070 --> 00:32:18,350
The whole system is fed exclusively by DC.

314
00:32:20,150 --> 00:32:34,770
And since the ammeter scale is pretty coarse, we'll use this ammeter with a 1 A scale to clearly see the load's current draw.

315
00:32:36,330 --> 00:32:38,970
One more important note.

316
00:32:39,170 --> 00:32:52,810
We've seen tons of videos online where lamps light up and the person says "but it's lit at 60%" or "30%".

317
00:32:53,700 --> 00:32:57,590
When I look at that, I always want to ask — how did you determine that?

318
00:32:59,230 --> 00:33:02,570
How much power is the lamp giving off?

319
00:33:03,090 --> 00:33:06,750
No lumens meter to measure flux intensity.

320
00:33:06,850 --> 00:33:08,960
Nothing — and you can't determine it by eye.

321
00:33:09,930 --> 00:33:15,910
So I recommend building a setup like this and not engaging in self-deception.

322
00:33:17,030 --> 00:33:19,690
And there's another interesting point.

323
00:33:19,810 --> 00:33:30,490
When people use lamps as a load and don't show device readings, and say by eye how much it looks like.

324
00:33:30,730 --> 00:33:41,430
Remember — at close distance, the camera over-represents the glow of a light source by about 20% over reality.

325
00:33:41,430 --> 00:33:50,310
So such people are always working with imaginary headroom.

326
00:33:51,330 --> 00:33:56,970
And I recommend self-checking, because self-deception.

327
00:33:57,210 --> 00:34:03,710
You can of course be in euphoria from your results, but that's how it is.

328
00:34:04,710 --> 00:34:10,270
There are groups of people in this happy oblivion.

329
00:34:11,090 --> 00:34:17,950
They constantly talk about something but never provide measurements.

330
00:34:18,370 --> 00:34:24,050
Before the experiment we need to sync the measuring devices on the load.

331
00:34:25,050 --> 00:34:26,690
100 watts wasn't there.

332
00:34:26,950 --> 00:34:28,630
75 watts.

333
00:34:28,750 --> 00:34:30,530
Turn on the third group.

334
00:34:32,810 --> 00:34:33,990
And the second lamp.

335
00:34:36,310 --> 00:34:38,270
25 watts.

336
00:34:38,450 --> 00:34:42,430
Note that there's 230 V.

337
00:34:43,670 --> 00:34:52,810
I don't think everyone knows that lamps give their nominal power only at 230 V.

338
00:34:52,810 --> 00:35:00,450
Only at 230 V on these two lamps will they deliver their 100 W of power.

339
00:35:00,850 --> 00:35:03,710
Not as light alone, of course, but as light plus heat.

340
00:35:04,290 --> 00:35:07,290
I mean the equivalent consumption.

341
00:35:09,030 --> 00:35:12,470
Now connecting to a DC source.

342
00:35:13,290 --> 00:35:16,950
Sync the measuring devices on DC.

343
00:35:16,950 --> 00:35:24,830
And we note the voltmeter and ammeter readings at 100 W.

344
00:35:27,150 --> 00:35:30,750
So I connected the load to the lab supply.

345
00:35:32,970 --> 00:35:37,410
Here are the current and voltage readings.

346
00:35:37,530 --> 00:35:40,690
230 V, 0.45 A.

347
00:35:41,460 --> 00:35:43,210
Look at the stand.

348
00:35:44,050 --> 00:35:53,650
Voltage is 230 V, current is 0.45 A.

349
00:35:53,650 --> 00:36:02,690
And here's the second ammeter that duplicates the scale on a bigger reading.

350
00:36:04,190 --> 00:36:10,590
So we see the measuring devices are synced with the power source.

351
00:36:10,690 --> 00:36:21,190
Now we'll determine by calculation how much power the lamps consume.

352
00:36:23,730 --> 00:36:35,450
230 V times 0.45 A gives 103.5 W.

353
00:36:36,450 --> 00:36:41,830
We'll test the device under a 103.5 W load.

354
00:36:42,350 --> 00:36:46,750
Now I'll write down the voltmeter and ammeter readings.

355
00:36:47,750 --> 00:36:51,130
And connect the load directly to the device.

356
00:36:52,830 --> 00:36:54,410
So, stand assembled.

357
00:36:56,570 --> 00:36:59,910
Power feeds these terminals.

358
00:37:00,550 --> 00:37:03,450
Pickup is from these terminals.

359
00:37:04,450 --> 00:37:05,250
Ammeter.

360
00:37:06,290 --> 00:37:07,670
Same lamps.

361
00:37:09,590 --> 00:37:10,150
Here they are.

362
00:37:12,290 --> 00:37:16,270
75 W and 25 W.

363
00:37:17,430 --> 00:37:22,550
And the stand also has another ammeter and voltmeter.

364
00:37:23,990 --> 00:37:32,590
This is the control consumption — in this case the PWM regulator driver.

365
00:37:33,450 --> 00:37:41,990
And now I'll bring the supply voltage up to the lamp nominal.

366
00:37:42,170 --> 00:37:43,490
Raise voltage.

367
00:37:46,050 --> 00:37:47,910
60 V.

368
00:37:49,150 --> 00:37:50,370
The lamps are glowing.

369
00:37:51,150 --> 00:37:59,790
And usually in these cases people would say "they're glowing very dim", but on the lamp it's clearly twice as bright through the camera.

370
00:38:00,350 --> 00:38:04,550
And they'd say the lamp burns at this many percent.

371
00:38:05,790 --> 00:38:09,510
Right now there's 98 V on the lamp.

372
00:38:11,630 --> 00:38:13,690
Almost 0.3 A.

373
00:38:14,750 --> 00:38:16,370
Raising to nominal.

374
00:38:17,370 --> 00:38:24,690
You see voltage growing on the load and it starts shining brighter.

375
00:38:26,130 --> 00:38:30,630
We need the same reading as in measurements — 230 V.

376
00:38:32,030 --> 00:38:33,590
Now set.

377
00:38:35,770 --> 00:38:38,470
There — caught it, 230 V.

378
00:38:39,470 --> 00:38:40,390
Fix it.

379
00:38:42,330 --> 00:38:47,230
1.1 A, 0.02 at 111 V.

380
00:38:48,890 --> 00:38:56,270
Voltage on the lamps, current — same as measured, 0.45 A.

381
00:38:58,650 --> 00:39:06,470
So this device gives 230 V and the current.

382
00:39:08,470 --> 00:39:10,970
And so the load glows.

383
00:39:15,380 --> 00:39:19,180
Now let's calculate consumed power.

384
00:39:19,840 --> 00:39:22,180
111 V.

385
00:39:23,820 --> 00:39:26,500
So — 111 V.

386
00:39:28,460 --> 00:39:37,520
Multiply by 1.02 A.

387
00:39:40,840 --> 00:39:47,740
We get 113.22 W.

388
00:39:48,240 --> 00:39:51,840
Bring out the sheet.

389
00:39:52,880 --> 00:40:00,920
So — 113.22 W.

390
00:40:01,680 --> 00:40:16,320
And write 111 V, 1.02 A.

391
00:40:18,180 --> 00:40:25,000
So — now we can calculate this device's efficiency.

392
00:40:25,860 --> 00:40:27,340
Doing the calculation now.

393
00:40:28,300 --> 00:40:31,040
Efficiency is calculated with this formula.

394
00:40:34,280 --> 00:40:45,400
So P2 in our case is 103.5 W.

395
00:40:47,400 --> 00:40:50,480
Divide by P1.

396
00:40:52,580 --> 00:40:57,800
That's 113.22.

397
00:40:57,800 --> 00:41:03,720
And multiply by 100.

398
00:41:05,380 --> 00:41:13,120
We see the efficiency is 91%.

399
00:41:13,800 --> 00:41:24,240
If we subtract the control consumption, the efficiency of this device is 90%.

400
00:41:25,240 --> 00:41:29,460
During experiments I noticed an interesting thing.

401
00:41:29,560 --> 00:41:32,620
First I experimented with one bifilar.

402
00:41:33,720 --> 00:41:38,700
The same way as drawn in the schematic.

403
00:41:39,920 --> 00:41:41,960
The spike was captured.

404
00:41:44,120 --> 00:41:46,960
We'll look at the spike on the oscillogram further on.

405
00:41:47,800 --> 00:41:50,680
But the efficiency was pretty low.

406
00:41:51,040 --> 00:41:52,920
About 35%.

407
00:41:54,780 --> 00:41:58,240
I experimented a lot with various wires.

408
00:41:58,540 --> 00:42:00,160
And efficiency floated a lot.

409
00:42:01,180 --> 00:42:08,420
The distance between wires, the length, frequency, operating duty cycle — they all strongly affect this system.

410
00:42:09,100 --> 00:42:11,560
The produced and output power.

411
00:42:12,680 --> 00:42:20,000
The experiment showed that this circuit can have pretty high efficiency.

412
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:30,280
I want to note that the efficiency of modern converters reaches 85% with standard schemes.

413
00:42:30,780 --> 00:42:36,020
The efficiency of converters most radio amateurs build is up to 80%.

414
00:42:36,760 --> 00:42:39,000
Most often 65–75%.

415
00:42:41,020 --> 00:42:45,140
This circuit isn't a step-up converter.

416
00:42:45,660 --> 00:42:47,220
Not step-down.

417
00:42:47,280 --> 00:42:48,820
Not a transformer.

418
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:51,300
Not a wire converter.

419
00:42:51,820 --> 00:42:57,500
Here — once again I want to emphasize — we have a closed system circuit.

420
00:42:57,740 --> 00:43:04,700
And an open system from which we take the response pulse from the environment.

421
00:43:05,800 --> 00:43:08,720
Now we do measurements of the oscillograms.

422
00:43:09,360 --> 00:43:15,000
And we confirm that this spike's polarity is always positive.

423
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:23,000
No matter how we connect the probe, no matter how we connect the oscilloscope's common wire.

424
00:43:24,140 --> 00:43:35,400
You need to understand that with regular circuits, if you connect the probe and swap the common, the polarity changes.

425
00:43:35,720 --> 00:43:41,240
The oscilloscope shows deflection either to the negative or positive side of the scale.

426
00:43:41,240 --> 00:43:49,020
For measurements on this device, the spike will be directed exclusively to the positive side.

427
00:43:49,720 --> 00:43:52,540
Which confirms the new effect.

428
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:56,340
It shows this spike isn't back EMF.

429
00:43:57,380 --> 00:44:02,440
And shows the presence in this system of a second particle.

430
00:44:02,560 --> 00:44:04,580
Why is the pulse positive?

431
00:44:04,700 --> 00:44:07,600
Because the particle itself is opposite to the electron.

432
00:44:08,220 --> 00:44:09,920
It's positively charged.

433
00:44:14,140 --> 00:44:22,180
First let's confirm the measurement is done exclusively by DC on this load.

434
00:44:22,840 --> 00:44:29,920
You can see I connected an oscilloscope channel to the device output.

435
00:44:30,100 --> 00:44:35,380
Specifically, the connection is now on this capacitor.

436
00:44:36,480 --> 00:44:42,200
And we'll observe the beam deflection on DC.

437
00:44:42,200 --> 00:44:44,960
Raise voltage to power.

438
00:44:45,320 --> 00:44:48,660
You see — zero point.

439
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:51,320
Voltage growth.

440
00:44:51,660 --> 00:44:52,320
You can see.

441
00:44:54,340 --> 00:44:56,160
Voltage grows.

442
00:44:59,840 --> 00:45:01,560
230 V.

443
00:45:03,100 --> 00:45:05,120
Load works.

444
00:45:06,120 --> 00:45:08,320
Here's the voltage.

445
00:45:08,560 --> 00:45:12,660
We see the measurement is exclusively on DC.

446
00:45:12,720 --> 00:45:16,180
Change DC.

447
00:45:19,060 --> 00:45:26,780
Now I moved the yellow oscilloscope channel to the PWM regulator control.

448
00:45:27,600 --> 00:45:29,760
The oscillogram is present here.

449
00:45:30,600 --> 00:45:36,880
Frequency is now 9.3 kHz for the control.

450
00:45:38,140 --> 00:45:45,040
The blue oscilloscope channel is on one of the bifilar leads.

451
00:45:46,380 --> 00:45:48,940
I connected it at this point.

452
00:45:49,600 --> 00:45:50,460
Before the diode.

453
00:45:51,300 --> 00:45:56,440
Because after the diode we'll have the DC we just observed.

454
00:45:56,440 --> 00:45:58,880
Apply power.

455
00:46:00,400 --> 00:46:06,740
And first we'll observe this oscillogram at small load.

456
00:46:06,840 --> 00:46:14,160
That means we applied a small supply voltage and it isn't at nominal.

457
00:46:15,120 --> 00:46:16,500
Raise voltage.

458
00:46:18,800 --> 00:46:22,340
You see exactly this oscillogram.

459
00:46:23,160 --> 00:46:32,340
I showed this oscillogram so we'd see the triggering effect happens when the transistor closes.

460
00:46:33,260 --> 00:46:34,120
Watch here.

461
00:46:34,920 --> 00:46:38,660
Now this is the transistor opening.

462
00:46:39,840 --> 00:46:42,200
Operation time, transistor closing.

463
00:46:42,460 --> 00:46:44,800
You can see by the scale.

464
00:46:45,760 --> 00:46:50,900
During opening the supply voltage drops to zero.

465
00:46:50,900 --> 00:46:58,160
And when the transistor closes — supply voltage rises.

466
00:46:58,300 --> 00:47:05,220
That is — the FET inverts voltage on DC.

467
00:47:06,620 --> 00:47:08,080
Here's this oscillogram.

468
00:47:08,520 --> 00:47:11,760
Now this oscillogram at these parameters.

469
00:47:12,680 --> 00:47:17,080
Now we raise the load to nominal.

470
00:47:18,080 --> 00:47:21,470
We watch how the oscillogram changes.

471
00:47:22,300 --> 00:47:26,340
Now we change the sweep per cell.

472
00:47:28,600 --> 00:47:30,520
Now 200 V per cell.

473
00:47:34,300 --> 00:47:35,020
There you see.

474
00:47:39,160 --> 00:47:40,260
Raise.

475
00:47:43,190 --> 00:47:46,580
The lamps are practically at nominal.

476
00:47:47,460 --> 00:47:48,740
Here's 230 V.

477
00:47:49,300 --> 00:47:57,140
And we can examine this oscillogram in detail.

478
00:47:58,260 --> 00:48:01,180
Lamps under nominal.

479
00:48:03,020 --> 00:48:11,960
And we see that this effect actually happens after the switch closes.

480
00:48:14,720 --> 00:48:18,640
This is the picture at nominal load.

481
00:48:18,740 --> 00:48:20,240
At the same point.

482
00:48:21,820 --> 00:48:25,400
Here's the oscillogram you can observe.

483
00:48:26,340 --> 00:48:27,660
Now a third variant.

484
00:48:27,940 --> 00:48:32,720
Now we disconnect the load and raise voltage from zero.

485
00:48:32,820 --> 00:48:37,120
We'll specifically see the response pulse from the environment.

486
00:48:38,380 --> 00:48:41,860
You see this is synced — drawn over time.

487
00:48:42,540 --> 00:48:47,500
And this cut top is part of the overall pulse.

488
00:48:49,060 --> 00:48:50,180
Here.

489
00:48:52,520 --> 00:48:56,200
So — disconnect the load, the third group.

490
00:48:57,520 --> 00:49:00,480
And raise voltage.

491
00:49:02,600 --> 00:49:05,240
You see the pulse forming.

492
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:24,000
And at supply voltage 12 V, the ammeter shows pretty high potential.

493
00:49:25,380 --> 00:49:29,120
I'll set it up a bit so the scale is visible.

494
00:49:30,820 --> 00:49:34,260
Let it be 300 V so the device doesn't blow.

495
00:49:35,260 --> 00:49:41,340
300 V forms without load, consumption 0.08 A at 23 V.

496
00:49:42,980 --> 00:49:47,940
Now expand the pulse per cell.

497
00:49:48,540 --> 00:49:52,420
Now the sweep is 100 V per cell.

498
00:49:53,440 --> 00:50:02,480
And we see that the amplitude is almost 3.5 cells — practically 350 V.

499
00:50:02,480 --> 00:50:10,920
And the device captures this reading on DC.

500
00:50:12,140 --> 00:50:15,100
Now brought up to 300 — even higher.

501
00:50:16,280 --> 00:50:21,440
The voltage grows very fast, nonlinearly.

502
00:50:22,040 --> 00:50:28,480
And we also see that when the switch opens, we have nothing.

503
00:50:28,720 --> 00:50:30,500
Switch operation time, nothing.

504
00:50:30,500 --> 00:50:33,460
And when it closes — we have the spike.

505
00:50:34,920 --> 00:50:39,560
So now — on the picture this is all shown.

506
00:50:40,340 --> 00:50:44,400
Now specifically look at the most interesting moment.

507
00:50:45,080 --> 00:50:47,840
The polarity of this spike.

508
00:50:48,380 --> 00:50:54,180
To observe the polarity I left one yellow oscilloscope channel.

509
00:50:55,140 --> 00:50:57,620
And pay attention to where it's connected now.

510
00:50:57,620 --> 00:51:01,460
Minus power comes here, plus here.

511
00:51:02,260 --> 00:51:08,420
Now the oscilloscope common is connected to the minus of the power source.

512
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:15,660
If you look at the schematic, the oscilloscope common is now at this point.

513
00:51:16,560 --> 00:51:24,500
The probe itself is at point 2 — before the diode, on one of the bifilar leads.

514
00:51:25,500 --> 00:51:27,400
Voltage not applied.

515
00:51:29,500 --> 00:51:31,860
Add... and we see.

516
00:51:33,120 --> 00:51:37,780
The pulse polarity relative to zero is strictly positive.

517
00:51:39,040 --> 00:51:50,480
During the experiment I'll switch the probe's common wire to the positive power terminal.

518
00:51:50,480 --> 00:51:57,040
While the probe itself stays on the same bifilar.

519
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:00,780
Disconnect the probe.

520
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:05,340
Connect to plus.

521
00:52:07,360 --> 00:52:10,680
And we see the polarity didn't change.

522
00:52:11,120 --> 00:52:14,420
Now let's play with the supply voltage.

523
00:52:15,120 --> 00:52:16,660
Amplitude changes.

524
00:52:17,660 --> 00:52:20,200
But polarity doesn't.

525
00:52:21,480 --> 00:52:25,320
This experiment shows the phenomenon is new.

526
00:52:26,220 --> 00:52:32,920
This phenomenon isn't back EMF relative to the input power potential.

527
00:52:33,900 --> 00:52:39,780
And this phenomenon is accompanied by a purely positive potential.

528
00:52:40,120 --> 00:52:44,380
That's this spike in the system.

529
00:52:47,330 --> 00:52:58,490
And you can see that switching the probe to other bifilars won't change the readings.

530
00:52:58,650 --> 00:52:59,750
Moved to another one.

531
00:53:00,530 --> 00:53:05,290
The readings stayed in positive polarity.

532
00:53:10,760 --> 00:53:12,850
So, summing up the experiment.

533
00:53:14,080 --> 00:53:18,700
During measurements we found out that building devices on this principle is possible.

534
00:53:18,700 --> 00:53:23,860
And the device has pretty high efficiency.

535
00:53:24,620 --> 00:53:27,340
And an interesting phenomenon was also found.

536
00:53:27,480 --> 00:53:35,220
During which it turned out that a second particle in positive polarity exists.

537
00:53:35,280 --> 00:53:39,000
Responsible for transferring electric energy in nature.

538
00:53:40,180 --> 00:53:49,300
We also found out the environment responds with a high-amplitude pulse.

539
00:53:50,020 --> 00:53:54,920
Much bigger than the pulse at the system's input.

540
00:53:55,580 --> 00:54:03,640
That way the environment tries to balance out the imbalance we create in coils of this type.

541
00:54:04,640 --> 00:54:14,700
By the way — the environment always strives to balance everything to an energy equilibrium.

542
00:54:16,040 --> 00:54:19,940
The same principle applied to inductors.

543
00:54:20,160 --> 00:54:26,020
Several turns near a classical Tesla transformer.

544
00:54:27,320 --> 00:54:29,620
The principle is very similar.

545
00:54:29,620 --> 00:54:39,000
We send a pulse, after which a rarefaction happens around the coil — around its inductor.

546
00:54:39,720 --> 00:54:45,140
And after this the environment strives to extinguish this rarefaction.

547
00:54:45,840 --> 00:54:52,100
And it acts, if you can say so, with its whole mass, suppressing this disturbance.

548
00:54:52,940 --> 00:54:58,180
And this is also accompanied by a high-polarity spike.

549
00:54:58,180 --> 00:55:07,300
And since on the path of this pulse there's a multi-turn solenoid, it slows this movement of the environment.

550
00:55:09,480 --> 00:55:18,660
Its crystal lattice gets excited, and on the Tesla coil we have very high potential.

551
00:55:18,660 --> 00:55:29,880
By the way — pay attention that the Tesla coil is a wonderful tool that separates the electron-positron pair into two components.

552
00:55:30,980 --> 00:55:37,160
It sends the electrons to ground, and the positrons accumulate at the hot end.

553
00:55:37,160 --> 00:55:47,320
Since the positrons are at the hot end, the surrounding environment — the electrons — try to combine with the positrons.

554
00:55:47,460 --> 00:55:52,640
And form an electrically and magnetically neutral electron-positron pair.

555
00:55:53,400 --> 00:56:06,600
That's exactly why charge flows toward the hot end of the Tesla coil, not the other way, as for example with devices built on other high-voltage sources.

556
00:56:07,160 --> 00:56:12,640
There the charge flows from the hot end of the device on the contrary.
